    </div>
    <div class="finding-body">
      <h4>Description</h4>
      <p>The tool accepts bash commands generated by the LLM and executes them via <code>std::process::Command</code>. While heavily validated, the LLM could be influenced by prompt injection to craft commands that bypass heuristic checks.</p>

      <h4>Affected Code</h4>
<pre class="code"><span class="cmt">// bash_validation.rs:103 &mdash; Read-only validation gate</span>
<span class="kw">pub fn</span> <span class="fn">validate_read_only</span>(command: &amp;<span class="type">str</span>, mode: <span class="type">PermissionMode</span>) -&gt; <span class="type">ValidationResult</span> {
    <span class="kw">if</span> mode != <span class="type">PermissionMode</span>::ReadOnly {
        <span class="kw">return</span> <span class="type">ValidationResult</span>::Allow;
    }
    <span class="kw">let</span> first_command = <span class="fn">extract_first_command</span>(command);
    <span class="kw">for</span> &amp;write_cmd <span class="kw">in</span> WRITE_COMMANDS { ... }
    <span class="kw">for</span> &amp;state_cmd <span class="kw">in</span> STATE_MODIFYING_COMMANDS { ... }
}</pre>

      <h4>Current Guardrails</h4>
      <p><span class="status protected"><span class="dot"></span> Read-only command blocklist (30+ commands)</span></p>
      <p><span class="status protected"><span class="dot"></span> Destructive pattern detection (fork bombs, rm -rf /)</span></p>
      <p><span class="status protected"><span class="dot"></span> Permission mode gating per command</span></p>
      <p><span class="status protected"><span class="dot"></span> Path traversal heuristics</span></p>
      <p><span class="status partial"><span class="dot"></span> Sandbox support (Linux only)</span></p>

      <h4>Gap Analysis</h4>
      <p>Blocklist approach is inherently incomplete &mdash; novel command combinations, aliased binaries, or encoded payloads (e.g., <code>python3 -c "..."</code>, <code>perl -e "..."</code>) can bypass first-command extraction. The <code>extract_first_command</code> parser splits on whitespace which may miss shell metacharacters.</p>

      <div class="recommendation">
        <strong>Recommendation:</strong> (1) Complement blocklist with allowlist of known-safe commands for read-only mode. (2) Add sandbox enforcement as default on Linux. (3) Consider integrating <code>seccomp-bpf</code> filters for fine-grained syscall control. (4) Log all executed commands to an audit trail for post-hoc review.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- HIGH-2: MCP Subprocess Environment -->
  <div class="finding" data-severity="high">
    <div class="finding-header">
      <span class="arrow">&#9654;</span>
      <span class="severity high">High</span>
      <span class="title">MCP Server Subprocess Inherits Unsanitized Environment</span>
      <span class="file-badge">mcp_stdio.rs / mcp_client.rs</span>
    </div>
    <div class="finding-body">
      <h4>Description</h4>
      <p>MCP servers are spawned as child processes via <code>tokio::process::Command</code>. Environment variables from configuration are passed directly without sanitization. A malicious <code>.claw.json</code> project config could inject environment variables like <code>LD_PRELOAD</code> or <code>PATH</code> to hijack execution.</p>

      <h4>Affected Code</h4>
<pre class="code"><span class="cmt">// mcp_client.rs &mdash; MCP transport config</span>
<span class="kw">pub struct</span> <span class="type">McpStdioTransport</span> {
    <span class="kw">pub</span> command: <span class="type">String</span>,
    <span class="kw">pub</span> args: <span class="type">Vec</span>&lt;<span class="type">String</span>&gt;,
    <span class="kw">pub</span> env: <span class="type">BTreeMap</span>&lt;<span class="type">String</span>, <span class="type">String</span>&gt;, <span class="cmt">// passed to subprocess directly</span>
}</pre>

      <h4>Current Guardrails</h4>
      <p><span class="status protected"><span class="dot"></span> Environment scoped to config-specified keys only</span></p>
      <p><span class="status gap"><span class="dot"></span> No blocklist for dangerous env vars (LD_PRELOAD, PATH, etc.)</span></p>
      <p><span class="status gap"><span class="dot"></span> Project-level config can define MCP servers (untrusted source)</span></p>

      <div class="recommendation">
        <strong>Recommendation:</strong> (1) Blocklist dangerous environment variable names (<code>LD_PRELOAD</code>, <code>LD_LIBRARY_PATH</code>, <code>DYLD_INSERT_LIBRARIES</code>, <code>PATH</code>). (2) Require user confirmation before spawning MCP servers defined in project-level config. (3) Run MCP subprocesses in a restricted environment rather than inheriting the full parent env.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- MEDIUM-1: Sandbox macOS Gap -->
  <div class="finding" data-severity="medium">
    <div class="finding-header">
      <span class="arrow">&#9654;</span>
      <span class="severity medium">Medium</span>
      <span class="title">Sandbox Namespace Isolation Unavailable on macOS</span>
      <span class="file-badge">sandbox.rs</span>
    </div>
    <div class="finding-body">
      <h4>Description</h4>
      <p>Linux namespace sandboxing (<code>unshare</code>) provides process/network isolation, but macOS has no equivalent. On macOS, the sandbox is effectively a no-op for namespace and network isolation, leaving only filesystem boundary checks as protection.</p>

      <h4>Affected Code</h4>
<pre class="code"><span class="cmt">// sandbox.rs:164</span>
<span class="kw">let</span> namespace_supported = <span class="fn">cfg!</span>(target_os = <span class="str">"linux"</span>) &amp;&amp; <span class="fn">unshare_user_namespace_works</span>();
<span class="kw">let</span> network_supported = namespace_supported; <span class="cmt">// false on macOS</span></pre>

      <h4>Current Guardrails</h4>
      <p><span class="status protected"><span class="dot"></span> Filesystem boundary enforcement (all platforms)</span></p>
      <p><span class="status protected"><span class="dot"></span> Fallback reason reporting when capabilities unavailable</span></p>
      <p><span class="status gap"><span class="dot"></span> No macOS sandbox-exec or App Sandbox integration</span></p>

      <div class="recommendation">
        <strong>Recommendation:</strong> Investigate macOS <code>sandbox-exec</code> (seatbelt) profiles or the App Sandbox entitlement API to provide filesystem and network isolation on macOS. At minimum, document the reduced security posture for macOS users.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- MEDIUM-2: OAuth Token Disk Storage -->
  <div class="finding" data-severity="medium">
    <div class="finding-header">
      <span class="arrow">&#9654;</span>
      <span class="severity medium">Medium</span>
      <span class="title">OAuth Tokens Persisted to Disk Without Encryption</span>
      <span class="file-badge">oauth.rs</span>
    </div>
    <div class="finding-body">
      <h4>Description</h4>
      <p>OAuth access tokens and refresh tokens are serialized to disk as plaintext JSON. Any process or user with filesystem read access can extract these credentials.</p>

      <h4>Affected Code</h4>
<pre class="code"><span class="cmt">// oauth.rs:13 &mdash; Token struct persisted via serde</span>
<span class="kw">pub struct</span> <span class="type">OAuthTokenSet</span> {
    <span class="kw">pub</span> access_token: <span class="type">String</span>,
    <span class="kw">pub</span> refresh_token: <span class="type">Option</span>&lt;<span class="type">String</span>&gt;,
    <span class="kw">pub</span> expires_at: <span class="type">Option</span>&lt;<span class="type">u64</span>&gt;,
    <span class="kw">pub</span> scopes: <span class="type">Vec</span>&lt;<span class="type">String</span>&gt;,
}</pre>

      <h4>Current Guardrails</h4>
      <p><span class="status protected"><span class="dot"></span> PKCE (S256) for authorization code exchange</span></p>
      <p><span class="status protected"><span class="dot"></span> Token masking in log output</span></p>
      <p><span class="status partial"><span class="dot"></span> OS file permissions (relies on user-level access control)</span></p>
      <p><span class="status gap"><span class="dot"></span> No encryption-at-rest or OS keychain integration</span></p>

      <div class="recommendation">
        <strong>Recommendation:</strong> Integrate with platform keychains (macOS Keychain, Linux Secret Service / libsecret, Windows Credential Manager) for token storage. Alternatively, encrypt the token file with a key derived from machine-specific entropy.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- MEDIUM-3: Path Validation Heuristic -->
  <div class="finding" data-severity="medium">
    <div class="finding-header">
      <span class="arrow">&#9654;</span>
      <span class="severity medium">Medium</span>
      <span class="title">Bash Path Validation Uses Heuristic String Matching</span>
      <span class="file-badge">bash_validation.rs:360</span>
    </div>
    <div class="finding-body">
      <h4>Description</h4>
      <p>The <code>validate_paths</code> function detects <code>../</code> traversal and home-directory references using simple string matching. This can be bypassed with encoded paths, shell variable expansion (<code>$(...)</code>), or symlink-relative references.</p>

      <h4>Affected Code</h4>
<pre class="code"><span class="cmt">// bash_validation.rs:360</span>
<span class="kw">pub fn</span> <span class="fn">validate_paths</span>(command: &amp;<span class="type">str</span>, workspace: &amp;<span class="type">Path</span>) -&gt; <span class="type">ValidationResult</span> {
    <span class="kw">if</span> command.<span class="fn">contains</span>(<span class="str">"../"</span>) {
        <span class="kw">let</span> workspace_str = workspace.<span class="fn">to_string_lossy</span>();
        <span class="kw">if</span> !command.<span class="fn">contains</span>(&amp;*workspace_str) {
            <span class="kw">return</span> <span class="type">ValidationResult</span>::Warn { ... };
        }
    }
    <span class="kw">if</span> command.<span class="fn">contains</span>(<span class="str">"~/"</span>) || command.<span class="fn">contains</span>(<span class="str">"$HOME"</span>) {
        <span class="kw">return</span> <span class="type">ValidationResult</span>::Warn { ... };
    }
}</pre>

      <h4>Gap</h4>
      <p>Does not detect: <code>$(cd /etc &amp;&amp; cat passwd)</code>, <code>eval</code>-based expansion, backtick substitution, or symlink chains that reach outside workspace.</p>

      <div class="recommendation">
        <strong>Recommendation:</strong> Expand validation to cover shell substitution patterns (<code>$()</code>, backticks, <code>eval</code>, <code>source</code>). For write commands, resolve the actual target path after shell expansion rather than pattern-matching the raw command string.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- MEDIUM-4: Hook Permission Override -->
  <div class="finding" data-severity="medium">
    <div class="finding-header">
      <span class="arrow">&#9654;</span>
      <span class="severity medium">Medium</span>
      <span class="title">Hooks Can Override Permission Decisions</span>
      <span class="file-badge">hooks.rs / permissions.rs</span>
    </div>
    <div class="finding-body">
      <h4>Description</h4>
      <p>Hooks execute shell commands and can return <code>PermissionOverride::Allow</code>, which bypasses normal permission evaluation. While hooks are user-configured, a compromised or malicious project-level config could define hooks that auto-approve dangerous operations.</p>

      <h4>Affected Code</h4>
<pre class="code"><span class="cmt">// permissions.rs:196 &mdash; Hook overrides evaluated early</span>
<span class="kw">match</span> context.<span class="fn">override_decision</span>() {
    <span class="type">Some</span>(<span class="type">PermissionOverride</span>::Allow) =&gt; {
        <span class="kw">if</span> allow_rule.<span class="fn">is_some</span>() || current_mode == <span class="type">PermissionMode</span>::Allow
            || current_mode &gt;= required_mode {
            <span class="kw">return</span> <span class="type">PermissionOutcome</span>::Allow;
        }
    }
}</pre>

      <h4>Mitigation Note</h4>
      <p>The code does check <code>ask_rule</code> even when a hook says Allow (line 220), which limits the override scope. Deny rules always take precedence (line 182).</p>

      <div class="recommendation">
        <strong>Recommendation:</strong> (1) Clearly separate user-level hooks from project-level hooks in trust evaluation. (2) Add an audit log entry whenever a hook overrides a permission check. (3) Consider requiring user confirmation when project-level hooks attempt Allow overrides.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- LOW-1: No Rate Limiting -->
  <div class="finding" data-severity="low">
    <div class="finding-header">
      <span class="arrow">&#9654;</span>
      <span class="severity low">Low</span>
      <span class="title">No Rate Limiting on Tool Execution</span>
      <span class="file-badge">runtime (general)</span>
    </div>
    <div class="finding-body">
      <h4>Description</h4>
      <p>There is no built-in rate limiting on how many tool calls the LLM can make per unit of time. A misbehaving model loop could generate rapid file operations or bash commands.</p>
      <h4>Current Mitigations</h4>
      <p><span class="status protected"><span class="dot"></span> Timeout support per individual bash command</span></p>
      <p><span class="status protected"><span class="dot"></span> File size limits (10 MB read/write)</span></p>
      <div class="recommendation">
        <strong>Recommendation:</strong> Add configurable per-minute limits on tool invocations, particularly for bash execution and file write operations.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- LOW-2: Write Redirection Detection -->
  <div class="finding" data-severity="low">
    <div class="finding-header">
      <span class="arrow">&#9654;</span>
      <span class="severity low">Low</span>
      <span class="title">Write Redirection Detection Is Simple String Match</span>
      <span class="file-badge">bash_validation.rs:97</span>
    </div>
    <div class="finding-body">
      <h4>Description</h4>
      <p>Write redirections (<code>&gt;</code>, <code>&gt;&gt;</code>, <code>&gt;&amp;</code>) are detected by checking if the command string contains these characters. This triggers false positives for quoted strings and misses redirections inside subshells or variables.</p>

      <h4>Affected Code</h4>
<pre class="code"><span class="cmt">// bash_validation.rs:97</span>
<span class="kw">const</span> WRITE_REDIRECTIONS: &amp;[&amp;<span class="type">str</span>] = &amp;[<span class="str">"&gt;"</span>, <span class="str">"&gt;&gt;"</span>, <span class="str">"&gt;&amp;"</span>];
<span class="cmt">// Line 144: simple contains check</span>
<span class="kw">for</span> &amp;redir <span class="kw">in</span> WRITE_REDIRECTIONS {
    <span class="kw">if</span> command.<span class="fn">contains</span>(redir) { <span class="kw">return</span> Block; }
}</pre>

      <div class="recommendation">
        <strong>Recommendation:</strong> Use a shell-aware tokenizer to distinguish actual redirections from characters inside quoted strings or variables.
      </div>
    </div>
